@tbl-one reveals several critical insights about border quarantine during the Delta wave. The data demonstrates a striking exponential relationship between vaccine efficacy and outbreak protection. While 50% efficacy vaccines provided only modest improvements (extending outbreak timelines from the baseline of 17 days to 22-35 days), 90% efficacy vaccines created extraordinary protection, extending the timeframe to 2,000-3,000 days at full population coverage - representing an improvement of nearly two orders of magnitude.

The most remarkable finding is the powerful threshold effect observed with high-efficacy vaccines. At 90% efficacy, each increase in population coverage produces dramatically larger gains in protection. For R₀ = 6, moving from 20% to 100% coverage extends the outbreak timeline from 500 to 3,000 days - a sixfold increase in protection. This exponential benefit is even more pronounced than linear models would predict, highlighting the critical importance of achieving both high vaccine efficacy and broad population coverage.

